05711nam a22007575i 9780822382225DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19921992ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223822257 a10.1515/97808223822252doi  a(DE-B1597)552653  a(OCoLC)841913359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3534b.P76 1992 7aMUS0350002bisacsh00aPresent Tense :bRock & Roll and Culture /cAnthony DeCurtis. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1992] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (332 p.) :b12 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tThe Eighties -- tThe Church of the Sonic Guitar -- tThe Enemy Within: Censorship in Rock Music in the 1950s -- tA Corpse in Your Mouth: Adventures of a Metaphor, or Modern Cannibalism -- tWhy Don't We Do It in the Classroom? -- tPlaying for England -- tRock &Roll as a Cultural Practice -- tTracking -- tSignposts on the Road to Nowhere: Laurie Anderson's Crisis of Meaning -- tConcerning the Progress of Rock &Roll -- tLos Angeles, 1999 -- tSexual Mobilities in Bruce Springsteen: Performance as Commentary -- tAbout a Salary or Reality?-Rap's Recurrent Conflict -- tVoguing at the Carnival: Desire and Pleasure on MTV -- tLiving by Night in the Land of Opportunity: Observations on Life in a Rock &Roll Band -- tIndex -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe most compelling art form to emerge from the United States in the second half of the twentieth century, rock & roll stands in an edgy relationship with its own mythology, its own musicological history and the broader culture in which it plays a part. In Present Tense, Anthony DeCurtis brings together writers from a wide variety of fields to explore how rock & roll is made, consumed, and experienced in our time.In this collection, Greil Marcus creates a collage of words and pictures that evokes and explores Elvis Presley's grisly fate as an American cultural image, while Robert Palmer tells the gripping tale of the origins and meanings of the electric guitar. Rap music, MTV, and the issue of gender identity in the work of Bruce Springsteen all undergo thorough examination; rock & roll's complex relationship with the forces of censorship gets a remarkably fresh reading; and the mainstreaming of rock & roll in the 1980s is detailed and analyzed. And, in an interview with Laurie Anderson and an essay by Atlanta musician Jeff Calder, the artists speak for themselves.Contributors. Jeff Calder, Anthony DeCurtis, Mark Dery, Paul Evans, Glenn Gass, Trent Hill, Michael Jarrett, Alan Light, Greil Marcus, Robert Palmer, Robert B. Ray, Dan Rubey, David R. Shumway, Martha Nell Smith, Paul Smith  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 0aRock musicxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rock.2bisacsh1 aLight, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeCurtis, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubey, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShumway, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeCurtis, Anthony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGass, Glenn1 aGass, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcus, Greil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Trent1 aCalder, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcus, Greil1 aDery, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Martha Nell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator